INSTRUCTIONS FOR ACCESSING THE SOURCE CODE REPOSITORY

You can access CVS remotely if you have the cvs software installed and
in your path on your local machine.  These are the environment 
variables that CVS requires, using csh syntax:

setenv CVSROOT user@hamlet.compbio.ucsf.edu:/usr/local/cvsroot
setenv CVS_SERVER /usr/bin/cvs
setenv CVS_RSH ssh

Instructions for using an ssh authentication agent to bypass
continually entering one's password are at the end of this letter.

Alternatively, you can logon to hamlet with ssh and access CVS 
directly:

setenv CVSROOT /usr/local/cvsroot
setenv CVS_SERVER /usr/bin/cvs
setenv CVS_RSH sh

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
RULES FOR USING THE REPOSITORY

1)  You must subscribe to the DOCK developers list server (contact 
John Irwin jji@cgl.ucsf.edu if you have not received an email).  In 
addition to whatever emails you send to other developers, please post 
regularly to the list server.  These discussions will be distributed to 
everyone and will be archived for future reference.  It will also be 
used to deliver group messages like bug fixes and release announcements. 
 
2)  You must thoroughly document all committed changes in the log 
file.  These comments must be transparent enough that other developers 
will be able to understand what has been changed.  In other words, these
should not be short hand notes to yourself but complete descriptions.

3)  Remove all compiled executables and object files before committing 
the changes.  The diff function used in merging depends on character 
comparison and binary files will create complications.

4)  Do not use the import command.  For some reason, in our version of
cvs server, the import command creates files on sub-sub-sub branches 
(ie version 1.1.1.1.1.1).  This will create issues later on when you are
 attempting to merge versions.  If you need to add a large number of 
files recursively through folders, use the following commands instead:

    cvs add * #create the folders
    cvs add `find . -name CVS -prune -o -name '*'` #add the files

5)  Changes to the code that will modify functions that you have not 
personally developed on the trunk must be discussed before they can be 
implemented.  Any change that you would like to make to the core 
functions of the code must be discussed by ALL the contacts before it 
can be implemented.  These modifications will effect everyone and we 
would like to both reduce the headaches in integrating the new code 
and enable everyone to have access to the modifications as soon as 
possible.
  
6)  All new branches must be named after the appropriate lab you are in.
You can create as many new branches as you need, but the name MUST start
with the name of the lab you are in.  This will prevent overwriting other
branches that may have similar names (see COMMONLY USED COMMANDS for 
instructions on how to make a new branch).

7)  Do not download other people's code (outside of the trunk) without 
their permission.  This rule is a courtesy to the other developers and 
will allow them to notify you if there are issues with the code.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
RECOMMENDATIONS FOR USING DOCK CVS SERVER

1)  Commit tested development code to the cvs server frequently.  This 
makes your contributions available to the other coders and eases 
transitions when releases approach.

2)  You will be notified by email when there are bug fixes added to the 
trunk.  When you receive these emails, update your code to ensure you do
not lose these fixes in your work.

3)  Communication will be essential for this process to run smoothly.  
Please strive to overuse the list server and to royally irritate all 
contacts.  It will make life easier for everyone when we 
are doing the releases.

