SSH AUTHENTICATION AGENT INSTRUCTIONS

This procedure will replace the password request on a per
cvs command basis with a single passphrase entry on login.
The three steps in the procedure are
public and private key generation on your local machine, creation of your
ssh authorized key file on the machine containing the cvs repository,
and addition of the ssh authentication agent processing to your local
machine dot (startup) file.

1.  Key generation
On your local machine execute the command
ssh-keygen -t dsa

$HOME/.ssh/id_dsa.pub
is the default location for the key.
Follow the usual common sense rules for your passphrase.

2.  Authorized key file creation
CVS accounts are on hamlet.compbio.ucsf.edu.
On your local machine execute the commands
ssh user@hamlet.compbio.ucsf.edu mkdir .ssh
cd $HOME/.ssh
scp id_dsa.pub user@hamlet.compbio.ucsf.edu:.ssh/authorized_keys

3.  Startup file modification
On your local machine add these lines, which use csh syntax,
to your .login file
    set jamesbond = $HOME/.ssh/secretagent
    rm -f $jamesbond
    ssh-agent >! $jamesbond
    source $jamesbond
    ssh-add


If you desire to use ssh agent authentication for additional local
machines then repeat step 1 on those machines and append the additional
public keys to the authorized key file on hamlet.

